{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503668"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:05:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:05:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2065"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2065"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.12,0.55,0.1,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53675"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2065"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39143"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"2450"},{"type":"tags","id":"3026"},{"type":"tags","id":"3205"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"5831"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"12914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"62"},{"type":"contributions","id":"63"},{"type":"contributions","id":"64"},{"type":"contributions","id":"580"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42446"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53675"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department accompanied by a social worker. She was recently admitted to hospital for an intentional suicide attempt by self-harm but self-discharged after her wounds were sutured. She has a history of depression treated with antidepressants, gambling, deliberate self-harm, and substance abuse. She lives with her partner, their two-year-old daughter, his 10-year-old son, and her four-year-old daughter from a previous relationship. She reports ongoing suicidal ideation but has made no plans. She feels ambivalent about the most recent suicide attempt, stating she always feels \u0022empty\u0022. She continues to have a poor relationship with her partner but feels unable to leave him because of her daughter, although she feels disconnected from her at times. She denies any history of past sexual abuse. She feels angry at herself because she does not want to be abandoned despite their relationship. She is currently unemployed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears older than her stated age. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There are several superficial cuts over her wrists. She is cooperative but mildly agitated and makes poor eye contact. Her speech is pressured, and she interrupts mid-sentence, but there is no evidence of a formal thought disorder. Her affect is euthymic, irritable, and mood congruent. There is no evidence of perceptual disturbance. She is oriented and alert. She acknowledges her past psychiatric history and while she is ambivalent about the most recent suicide attempt, she gives no indication of current active suicidal plans.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Detention under Inpatient Treatment Order","Antidepressant medication","Dialectical behaviour therapy","Admission to rehabilitation facility","Electroconvulsive therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms consistent with borderline personality disorder (BPD). She demonstrates a pattern of unstable interpersonal relationships, impulsivity, recurrent suicidal behaviour, and feelings of emptiness, which are characteristic features of BPD. Comorbid major depressive disorder is also common in patients with BPD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDialectical behaviour therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (DBT) is considered a first-line treatment for BPD. It is a form of psychotherapy that aims to change behaviour and teach skills for stress management, emotion regulation, and interpersonal effectiveness. DBT has been shown to be effective in reducing self-harm behaviours, suicidal ideation, and improving overall functioning in patients with BPD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetention under Inpatient Treatment Order\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate at this stage, as the patient is not in imminent danger to herself or others. While patients with BPD often present with chronic suicidal ideation, they typically remain at a low to medium risk over many years. Involuntary admission is generally reserved for acute crises with imminent risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntidepressant medication\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not sufficient for treating BPD. While antidepressants may be used as adjuncts to psychotherapy to target specific symptoms (such as depressed mood or anxiety), they do not address the core features of BPD and are not considered a primary treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmission to rehabilitation facility\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically indicated for BPD. While the patient has a history of substance abuse, the primary focus should be on treating her BPD symptoms through outpatient psychotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectroconvulsive therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (ECT) has minimal evidence for treating BPD or BPD-related depression. It is generally reserved for severe, treatment-resistant major depressive disorder and is not a standard treatment for personality disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, psychotherapy, particularly DBT, is the principal treatment for BPD. Medications may be used as adjuncts to target specific symptoms, but they do not provide the long-term behavioural changes necessary for managing BPD. The chronic nature of BPD requires ongoing outpatient management rather than acute interventions like involuntary admission or ECT.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dialectical behaviour therapy is a first-line treatment for borderline personality disorder.","Patients with borderline personality disorder often present with chronic suicidal ideation and self-harm behaviours.","Psychotherapy is the principal treatment for borderline personality disorder, with medications used as adjuncts to target specific symptoms."],"references":["American Psychiatric Association. Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders: DSM-5. 5th ed. Arlington, VA: American Psychiatric Association, 2013:663-66.","Beatson JA, Rao S. Depression and borderline personality disorder. Med J Australia. 2013;199(6):S24-S27. Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2013/199/6/depression-and-borderline-personality-disorder","Storeb\u00f8 OJ, Stoffers\u2010Winterling JM, V\u00f6llm BA, et al. Psychological therapies for people with borderline personality disorder. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2018;2018(2):CD012955. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32368793/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39143"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2065"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39143"},"attributes":{"created